    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-04-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-04-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="155"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d155">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.34537/54.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-04-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 12, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 277.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s instruction No.
                        278,<note n="1" xml:id="d155fn1">The omissions appear under Naval Station at
                        Guantánamo and Claim for the cost of intervention in Cuba, <ref
                            target="#pg_118">pp. 118</ref> and <ref target="#pg_134"
                        >134</ref>.</note> of this date, which acknowledges the receipt of your
                    dispatch No. 700 of March 25, 1911,<note n="3" xml:id="d155fn3">Printed under
                        Naval Station at Guantánamo, <ref target="#pg_120">p. 120</ref>.</note> you
                    are informed that the attitude of this Government with regard to the final
                    settlement of the sovereignty over the Isle of Pines has been made clear in the
                    treaty signed at Washington on March. 2, 1904, which has been submitted to the
                    Senate for its approval but on which no action has as yet been taken. The
                    Department therefore considers that the wisest course is to allow the matter to
                    remain where it at present rests, and you will so inform the Cuban secretary of
                    state.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
